# No N+1 Database Query Patterns

The data-access layer talks to PostgreSQL via PostgREST with a **200-connection pool** (10 ECS tasks × 20). N+1 patterns fire one HTTP request per entity and can exhaust the pool, causing cascading failures across all services.

## Rules

### 1. Never use `Promise.all(items.map(i => i.save()))`

Use `Collection.saveMany(items)` instead. It chunks internally into bulk upserts.

```js
// BAD
await Promise.all(suggestions.map((s) => s.save()));

// GOOD
await Suggestion.saveMany(suggestionsToSave);
```

### 2. Never use N × `findById()` in a loop

Use `Collection.batchGetByKeys(keys)` for a single `.in()` query, then build a Map for O(1) lookup.

```js
// BAD
for (const id of ids) {
  const suggestion = await Suggestion.findById(id);
}

// GOOD
const keys = ids.map((id) => ({ suggestionId: id }));
const { data: suggestions } = await Suggestion.batchGetByKeys(keys);
const suggestionMap = new Map(suggestions.map((s) => [s.getId(), s]));
```

### 3. Never use `Promise.all(items.map(i => i.remove()))`

Use `Collection.removeByIds(ids)` for a single `DELETE ... WHERE id IN (...)`.

```js
// BAD
await Promise.all(suggestions.map((s) => s.remove()));

// GOOD
await Suggestion.removeByIds(suggestionsToRemove.map((s) => s.getId()));
```

## Quick Reference

| Instead of | Use |
|------------|-----|
| `Promise.all(items.map(i => i.save()))` | `Collection.saveMany(items)` |
| N × `Collection.findById(id)` | `Collection.batchGetByKeys(keys)` + Map |
| `Promise.all(items.map(i => i.remove()))` | `Collection.removeByIds(ids)` |

## Hot Spots

Watch for these patterns especially in:
- `src/utils/data-access.js` (syncSuggestions, reconcile, publish)
- Guidance handlers updating suggestions from AI responses
- Code-fix handlers applying patch data to suggestions
- Any loop over entities calling `.save()`, `.remove()`, or `findById()`
